1
00:00:12,653 --> 00:00:16,308
[SPEAKER_09]: Tonight, the first ever leaders general election climate debate.

2
00:00:16,730 --> 00:00:21,651
[SPEAKER_09]: They've all been invited to explain what they do about the emergency on planet Earth.

3
00:00:34,675 --> 00:00:35,156
[SPEAKER_09]: Good evening.

4
00:00:35,376 --> 00:00:41,766
[SPEAKER_09]: It is the biggest issue on the planet and today the European Parliament followed the UK's lead in declaring a climate emergency.

5
00:00:42,107 --> 00:00:50,440
[SPEAKER_09]: So tonight we are clearing the decks and devoting the whole of Channel 4 News to this one crisis in the first ever party leaders climate debate.

6
00:00:50,420 --> 00:00:53,183
[SPEAKER_09]: The leaders of Britain's biggest parties were all invited.

7
00:00:53,583 --> 00:00:54,464
[SPEAKER_09]: Five of them are here.

8
00:00:54,824 --> 00:01:00,990
[SPEAKER_09]: The Liberal Democrats, the Scottish National Party and Plaid Cymru, Labour and the Green Party of England and Wales.

9
00:01:01,471 --> 00:01:06,216
[SPEAKER_09]: We kept the invitations open to the leaders of the Conservative Party and the Brexit Party.

10
00:01:06,596 --> 00:01:08,778
[SPEAKER_09]: They have not taken up their places yet.

11
00:01:09,419 --> 00:01:18,688
[SPEAKER_09]: Instead, a reminder, the ice caps are melting as politicians around the globe fail to cut greenhouse gas emissions in time to stop rising temperatures.

12
00:01:18,668 --> 00:01:22,856
[SPEAKER_09]: Now, everyone here has grand rhetoric on what we need to do about the climate emergency.

13
00:01:23,257 --> 00:01:28,628
[SPEAKER_09]: Tonight, we want to test what they'd actually do in government for the next five years and beyond.

14
00:01:29,349 --> 00:01:34,059
[SPEAKER_09]: Also here are three experts to fact check and give us their view at the end of the debate.

15
00:01:34,500 --> 00:01:38,668
[SPEAKER_09]: But first, with the scale of the challenge, our chief correspondent, Alex Thompson.

16
00:02:07,758 --> 00:02:10,062
[SPEAKER_06]: The agony of climate change.

17
00:02:10,723 --> 00:02:15,811
[SPEAKER_06]: A koala burned but saved from Australia's recent raging bushfires.

18
00:02:16,492 --> 00:02:19,196
[SPEAKER_10]: What do we want?

19
00:02:19,216 --> 00:02:19,537
[SPEAKER_10]: Climate justice!

20
00:02:19,557 --> 00:02:19,978
[SPEAKER_10]: When do we want it?

21
00:02:19,998 --> 00:02:20,078
[SPEAKER_10]: Now!

22
00:02:20,098 --> 00:02:22,782
[SPEAKER_06]: From the carriageways to the courts, they get it.

23
00:02:23,103 --> 00:02:29,433
[SPEAKER_06]: We could face irreversible damage to the natural world and the collapse of our societies.

24
00:02:29,733 --> 00:02:30,795
[SPEAKER_06]: He gets it.

25
00:02:30,944 --> 00:02:32,125
[SPEAKER_02]: People are suffering.

26
00:02:32,906 --> 00:02:34,088
[SPEAKER_02]: People are dying.

27
00:02:34,148 --> 00:02:38,633
[SPEAKER_06]: She not only gets it, but gave it both barrels to the UN this year.

28
00:02:39,655 --> 00:02:41,657
[SPEAKER_06]: Even he finally gets it.

29
00:02:42,198 --> 00:02:42,598
[SPEAKER_06]: Neither.

30
00:02:43,419 --> 00:02:48,065
[SPEAKER_06]: But what does it take for UK politicians to act instead of talk?

31
00:02:48,625 --> 00:02:58,217
[SPEAKER_06]: As this year's biodiversity index showed, one in seven species across our islands is now heading for extinction because of human impact.

32
00:02:58,467 --> 00:03:02,651
[SPEAKER_06]: As predicted, prolonged drought-fuelled fires across the world.

33
00:03:03,192 --> 00:03:08,037
[SPEAKER_06]: Some man-made, as governments turn rainforest into beef burgers and palm oil.

34
00:03:09,058 --> 00:03:12,101
[SPEAKER_06]: Another year, too, of ferocious hurricanes and typhoons.

35
00:03:12,542 --> 00:03:17,607
[SPEAKER_06]: The super-intense storms climatologists predict as we overheat our planet.

36
00:03:18,628 --> 00:03:22,973
[SPEAKER_06]: And coming home, floods across Europe, from Venice to Doncaster.

37
00:03:24,083 --> 00:03:30,293
[SPEAKER_06]: Arctic glaciers at risk, threatening every coastal city in the world with catastrophic sea level rise.

38
00:03:31,175 --> 00:03:32,838
[SPEAKER_06]: We're going to have to do so much more.

39
00:03:33,078 --> 00:03:48,083
[SPEAKER_06]: That means the people across the lawn in that building are going to have to increase their carbon-cutting emissions ambitions fivefold just to keep pace with the 1.5 degrees C rise in global temperatures.

40
00:03:49,447 --> 00:03:52,231
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh, and the koala bear saved from the bushfires.

41
00:03:52,832 --> 00:03:54,775
[SPEAKER_06]: He was put down this week.

42
00:03:55,076 --> 00:03:56,758
[SPEAKER_06]: His wounds, untreatable.

43
00:03:57,679 --> 00:03:59,222
[SPEAKER_06]: His pain, unbearable.

44
00:04:09,037 --> 00:04:15,927
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's start with short opening statements from the leaders in alphabetical order, starting with the co-leader of the Green Party, Sian Berry.

45
00:04:17,088 --> 00:04:18,730
[SPEAKER_00]: Tonight, this is what you'll see.

46
00:04:19,310 --> 00:04:22,553
[SPEAKER_00]: Every leader on this stage will agree, with me.

47
00:04:22,953 --> 00:04:26,156
[SPEAKER_00]: They will all work hard to sound a little bit like the Green Party.

48
00:04:26,757 --> 00:04:28,438
[SPEAKER_00]: Some might even sound convincing.

49
00:04:29,279 --> 00:04:30,140
[SPEAKER_00]: It's progress.

50
00:04:30,460 --> 00:04:32,963
[SPEAKER_00]: But as you watch, ask yourself two important questions.

51
00:04:33,303 --> 00:04:36,086
[SPEAKER_00]: Do their plans match the scale of the emergency we face?

52
00:04:36,346 --> 00:04:41,050
[SPEAKER_00]: And do you trust them to get this done without more Greens in Parliament making sure of it?

53
00:04:41,671 --> 00:04:43,793
[SPEAKER_00]: If the answer is no, then vote Green.

54
00:04:44,393 --> 00:04:46,335
[SPEAKER_00]: If not now, when?

55
00:04:47,075 --> 00:04:47,541
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

56
00:04:47,642 --> 00:04:49,120
[SPEAKER_00]: And next Jeremy Corbyn.

57
00:04:49,437 --> 00:04:53,703
[SPEAKER_07]: This election is our last chance to tackle the climate and environment emergency.

58
00:04:54,264 --> 00:04:58,249
[SPEAKER_07]: The climate movement has changed our politics forever and Labour has listened.

59
00:04:58,690 --> 00:05:02,635
[SPEAKER_07]: Just 100 companies are responsible for 70% of emissions.

60
00:05:03,196 --> 00:05:07,562
[SPEAKER_07]: And you at home must not pay the price of the transition to a net zero economy.

61
00:05:08,043 --> 00:05:14,171
[SPEAKER_07]: Labour will kickstart a green industrial revolution, bringing new wealth to all parts of our country.

62
00:05:14,592 --> 00:05:18,617
[SPEAKER_07]: Labour is on your side and on the side of the environment.

63
00:05:18,597 --> 00:05:20,671
[SPEAKER_07]: It is time for real change.

64
00:05:21,597 --> 00:05:24,658
[SPEAKER_09]: Next, for Applied Cymru, its leader Adam Price.

65
00:05:25,617 --> 00:05:29,022
[SPEAKER_08]: As a new father, the climate crisis feels personal now.

66
00:05:29,744 --> 00:05:36,474
[SPEAKER_08]: My son is only one, but one day soon he's going to ask me, you had power, so what did you do?

67
00:05:37,275 --> 00:05:48,393
[SPEAKER_08]: What I want to do is to combine hope with urgency, to make a trinity of zeros, zero carbon, zero waste, zero poverty, our common goal by 2030.

68
00:05:48,453 --> 00:05:51,658
[SPEAKER_08]: To turn Wales into the world's test bed,

69
00:05:51,638 --> 00:05:57,861
[SPEAKER_08]: to make this moment not a tipping point of disaster, but a turning point of change.

70
00:05:58,403 --> 00:05:58,784
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

71
00:05:58,804 --> 00:06:01,193
[SPEAKER_09]: And now the leader of the SNP, Nicola Sturgeon.

72
00:06:01,325 --> 00:06:07,855
[SPEAKER_04]: Tackling the global climate emergency is a moral obligation and Scotland is already leading the way.

73
00:06:08,175 --> 00:06:18,791
[SPEAKER_04]: We have almost halved our emissions and now set a new legal target to reach net zero of all emissions by 2045, five years ahead of the rest of the UK.

74
00:06:19,331 --> 00:06:25,240
[SPEAKER_04]: That goes further than the Paris Agreement and beyond what international experts say is needed globally.

75
00:06:25,220 --> 00:06:34,017
[SPEAKER_04]: Our focus now is on taking the action to secure this transition in a fair way, and in partnership with other countries in the EU and beyond.

76
00:06:34,518 --> 00:06:40,589
[SPEAKER_04]: It is a big challenge, but one that we all must meet, and the SNP is determined to do so.

77
00:06:41,310 --> 00:06:43,735
[SPEAKER_09]: And now, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Jo Swinson.

78
00:06:45,149 --> 00:06:49,256
[SPEAKER_03]: The climate crisis is even more important than Brexit.

79
00:06:50,037 --> 00:06:52,141
[SPEAKER_03]: But Brexit is a climate crime.

80
00:06:53,002 --> 00:07:00,635
[SPEAKER_03]: It is morally wrong to leave our seat at the table and give up our influence to create the change we need right across the world.

81
00:07:01,517 --> 00:07:03,580
[SPEAKER_03]: We have two paths ahead of us.

82
00:07:03,830 --> 00:07:16,668
[SPEAKER_03]: one where our children inherit a poisoned planet, or one where our children breathe clean air, where going green is the easier, cheaper option, where we protect our planet for future generations.

83
00:07:17,409 --> 00:07:17,910
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you all.

84
00:07:17,930 --> 00:07:18,611
[SPEAKER_09]: So let's begin.

85
00:07:18,731 --> 00:07:20,393
[SPEAKER_09]: Our format is simple.

86
00:07:20,433 --> 00:07:25,420
[SPEAKER_09]: Each leader will get the chance to answer at least one question first, and then we'll freely debate it between everyone.

87
00:07:25,661 --> 00:07:28,825
[SPEAKER_09]: There's a lot to get through, so please keep your answers brief.

88
00:07:28,805 --> 00:07:34,115
[SPEAKER_09]: First, the Conservatives are committed to reaching the emissions target of net zero by 2050.

89
00:07:34,195 --> 00:07:40,547
[SPEAKER_09]: That means the amount of greenhouse gases we are putting into the atmosphere will be balanced by the amount we are taking out.

90
00:07:40,868 --> 00:07:42,992
[SPEAKER_09]: So is 2050 the right target?

91
00:07:43,453 --> 00:07:44,535
[SPEAKER_09]: Jeremy Corbyn.

92
00:07:44,515 --> 00:07:55,022
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, on the government's current target, they won't reach it until 2099 anyway, because they're simply not living up to the demands made of the Paris Climate Change Accord or indeed of their own statements.

93
00:07:55,644 --> 00:07:59,554
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we have to do everything we can to get to a 2030.

94
00:07:59,534 --> 00:08:14,541
[SPEAKER_07]: zero emissions target and we do that by investment in green energy jobs, solar, wind and wave power and we do that by creating jobs in transforming our energy consumption by retrofitting homes to make them environmentally sustainable.

95
00:08:14,861 --> 00:08:15,923
[SPEAKER_07]: We also have to work

96
00:08:15,903 --> 00:08:23,652
[SPEAKER_07]: on the global stage, because at the moment, it's going to be well into the end of this century before there's anywhere near sustainability on a global stage.

97
00:08:23,872 --> 00:08:27,176
[SPEAKER_07]: And by that time, temperatures will have gone up by three degrees centigrade.

98
00:08:27,216 --> 00:08:38,949
[SPEAKER_07]: And so I want to host COP26 next year to go further than Paris so that we can be leaders on the world stage in setting an agenda of achieving this degree of sustainability by 2030.

99
00:08:38,989 --> 00:08:40,391
[SPEAKER_09]: So Labour's aiming at 2030.

100
00:08:40,471 --> 00:08:43,935
[SPEAKER_09]: Nicola Sturgeon, I mean, you're making a big deal of going for 2045.

101
00:08:43,915 --> 00:08:48,221
[SPEAKER_09]: climate change said Scotland would be doing anyway?

102
00:08:48,421 --> 00:08:51,785
[SPEAKER_04]: It is what the Committee on Climate Change said is at the outer limits right now.

103
00:08:51,866 --> 00:08:54,369
[SPEAKER_04]: That is what we should be aiming for at the very latest.

104
00:08:54,409 --> 00:09:00,036
[SPEAKER_04]: What Scotland has done is pile on the pressure to meet higher targets earlier.

105
00:09:00,076 --> 00:09:06,565
[SPEAKER_04]: We are going beyond what the Committee on Climate Change has said for 2030, a 75% reduction in all emissions

106
00:09:06,545 --> 00:09:10,069
[SPEAKER_04]: by 2030, carbon neutrality by 2040.

107
00:09:10,269 --> 00:09:21,080
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, the IPCC, the international expert, says that the world needs to reach carbon neutrality by 2050 and half emissions, carbon emissions, by 2030.

108
00:09:21,520 --> 00:09:23,282
[SPEAKER_04]: So we are going beyond that.

109
00:09:23,362 --> 00:09:28,948
[SPEAKER_04]: And unlike the other leaders here, I'm actually in government, leading a government that is leading by example.

110
00:09:29,028 --> 00:09:31,451
[SPEAKER_04]: Our targets are the toughest anywhere in the world.

111
00:09:31,471 --> 00:09:32,772
[SPEAKER_04]: They include aviation,

112
00:09:32,752 --> 00:09:37,702
[SPEAKER_04]: shipping and they don't rely on international credits and that's the kind of ambition we need to see all countries take.

113
00:09:37,782 --> 00:09:39,285
[SPEAKER_09]: Adam Price, it's the opposite problem for you.

114
00:09:39,325 --> 00:09:46,660
[SPEAKER_09]: If Scotland has the resources to get there quicker, the Commission on Climate Change says Wales has less and yet you want to go quicker.

115
00:09:46,792 --> 00:10:00,383
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, yeah, and we need the power to do that, you know, so that we can actually use the huge advantages that we have in terms of the green jobs revolution, the fantastic marine energy resources that we have across all over our coastline.

116
00:10:00,443 --> 00:10:03,630
[SPEAKER_08]: But of course, at the moment, we don't have the power to tap into that potential.

117
00:10:03,650 --> 00:10:05,053
[SPEAKER_08]: We want to see that investment.

118
00:10:05,033 --> 00:10:10,365
[SPEAKER_08]: I have to say to Jeremy, of course, it was great to see the Labour motion at your conference coming out for 2030.

119
00:10:10,425 --> 00:10:13,291
[SPEAKER_08]: That's absolutely the right target.

120
00:10:13,432 --> 00:10:17,962
[SPEAKER_08]: But unfortunately, the manifesto says you want to get the majority of emissions by 2030.

121
00:10:18,202 --> 00:10:21,169
[SPEAKER_08]: A couple of countries that are already in the world have gone for 2030.

122
00:10:21,149 --> 00:10:23,713
[SPEAKER_08]: We need to show that same level of ambition.

123
00:10:23,873 --> 00:10:27,678
[SPEAKER_08]: We have the technology now to reach carbon neutrality by 2030.

124
00:10:28,059 --> 00:10:30,983
[SPEAKER_08]: Unfortunately, what's lacking is the political will.

125
00:10:31,023 --> 00:10:36,630
[SPEAKER_08]: That's the monuments to the lack of political leadership that we have either side of us here.

126
00:10:36,650 --> 00:10:37,592
[SPEAKER_08]: We've got to change that.

127
00:10:37,632 --> 00:10:41,497
[SPEAKER_08]: And the people that aren't represented here as well are the future generations.

128
00:10:41,637 --> 00:10:44,761
[SPEAKER_08]: We've got to be their voice and get to 2030 carbon neutrality.

129
00:10:44,782 --> 00:10:45,823
[SPEAKER_09]: So you're another 2030.

130
00:10:45,843 --> 00:10:47,325
[SPEAKER_09]: Joe Swinson, where are you?

131
00:10:47,677 --> 00:10:54,745
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, we think that it is absolutely possible to get there by 2045, but we should do this as quickly as we can.

132
00:10:54,765 --> 00:10:55,906
[SPEAKER_03]: So you're less ambitious?

133
00:10:56,027 --> 00:11:00,071
[SPEAKER_03]: No, because we should do it as quickly as we can and bring that date forward.

134
00:11:00,692 --> 00:11:09,942
[SPEAKER_03]: But the important thing is not only when we get to net zero, it's how quickly we cut emissions right now, how much carbon we take out of the atmosphere right now.

135
00:11:10,363 --> 00:11:13,827
[SPEAKER_03]: That is what is going to give us the best chance of saving our planet.

136
00:11:13,847 --> 00:11:16,570
[SPEAKER_03]: But can I inject a note of optimism?

137
00:11:16,550 --> 00:11:24,938
[SPEAKER_03]: I noticed in your film at the beginning, the fate of that koala at the end of it perhaps was a bit of a somber note.

138
00:11:25,078 --> 00:11:28,902
[SPEAKER_03]: And often in these climate discussions, that can be how it feels.

139
00:11:28,962 --> 00:11:30,143
[SPEAKER_03]: It can feel impossible.

140
00:11:30,764 --> 00:11:42,135
[SPEAKER_03]: When I was growing up in the 1980s, the big challenge that we were thinking about was the hole in the ozone layer and how we were going to deal with that and all of the negative impacts that had.

141
00:11:42,503 --> 00:11:48,197
[SPEAKER_03]: What gives me hope is that international action was taken, governments got together and agreed.

142
00:11:49,039 --> 00:11:55,895
[SPEAKER_03]: CFCs were cut by 98% and the hole in the ozone layer is now the smallest it has been for 30 years and looks like it will repair.

143
00:11:56,236 --> 00:11:58,521
[SPEAKER_03]: That shows me that we can solve this problem.

144
00:11:58,501 --> 00:12:05,630
[SPEAKER_09]: how credible is 2030, which is also your pledge, when the experts on the Committee on Climate Change just say that's too fast?

145
00:12:05,911 --> 00:12:10,076
[SPEAKER_00]: We have to do what the science demands, not what's politically convenient here.

146
00:12:10,116 --> 00:12:17,206
[SPEAKER_00]: And the key thing about a 2050 target is it leaves us with a 50% chance of tipping over into runaway climate chaos.

147
00:12:17,246 --> 00:12:21,051
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, would you cross a bridge with those odds of getting to the other side?

148
00:12:21,331 --> 00:12:25,977
[SPEAKER_00]: It's incredibly important that we do what the IPCC warned us about, which is

149
00:12:25,957 --> 00:12:28,501
[SPEAKER_00]: get involved in cutting emissions as quickly as possible.

150
00:12:28,521 --> 00:12:40,139
[SPEAKER_00]: Because when we do that, the sooner a target we set, the early action helps in terms of getting people's lives better and equality, and especially global equality as well.

151
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:45,948
[SPEAKER_00]: If we leave it too late, we end up using technology to solve the problem, some of which we don't already have.

152
00:12:46,049 --> 00:12:48,472
[SPEAKER_00]: So 2030 is the right target.

153
00:12:48,513 --> 00:12:53,280
[SPEAKER_00]: We shouldn't just give up on it and weaken it like Labour have done when things get difficult.

154
00:12:53,260 --> 00:12:57,907
[SPEAKER_00]: Our plans, our Green New Deal, are several times larger than any party who's here.

155
00:12:58,147 --> 00:12:59,489
[SPEAKER_00]: They will achieve that target.

156
00:12:59,509 --> 00:13:00,250
[SPEAKER_00]: We're not weakening.

157
00:13:00,270 --> 00:13:04,216
[SPEAKER_00]: And they put faith in people to achieve it from the bottom up as well as from the top down.

158
00:13:04,236 --> 00:13:05,258
[SPEAKER_07]: We're not weakening.

159
00:13:05,278 --> 00:13:06,259
[SPEAKER_07]: We're not giving up on it.

160
00:13:06,380 --> 00:13:07,641
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm determined to achieve it.

161
00:13:07,942 --> 00:13:10,746
[SPEAKER_07]: That's why I've put that in our manifesto.

162
00:13:10,726 --> 00:13:13,069
[SPEAKER_07]: we recognise there are huge problems on the way.

163
00:13:13,589 --> 00:13:19,515
[SPEAKER_07]: Adam made the point about Wales being part of a net zero emissions country in the future.

164
00:13:19,756 --> 00:13:20,697
[SPEAKER_07]: I absolutely agree with that.

165
00:13:20,757 --> 00:13:23,800
[SPEAKER_07]: That means very big investment in the Swansea Bay Lagoon.

166
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:29,206
[SPEAKER_07]: It means big investments all around the UK on wind farms and the solar energy jobs.

167
00:13:29,486 --> 00:13:30,727
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm determined to achieve it.

168
00:13:31,028 --> 00:13:40,598
[SPEAKER_07]: We recognise that we just cannot go on like this, but also we have to recognise we are one country in the whole world, so it's what Britain does on the world stage and particularly

169
00:13:40,578 --> 00:13:43,141
[SPEAKER_07]: particularly at the COP conference next year.

170
00:13:43,161 --> 00:13:51,290
[SPEAKER_03]: I totally agree that the role that we play internationally is so important.

171
00:13:51,690 --> 00:13:56,936
[SPEAKER_03]: But surely, you can see, that's why it's so important that we keep our seat at the European Union table.

172
00:13:56,976 --> 00:13:59,859
[SPEAKER_03]: Because we have led the way in Europe on this.

173
00:14:00,240 --> 00:14:01,321
[SPEAKER_03]: Europe has led the world.

174
00:14:01,361 --> 00:14:04,665
[SPEAKER_03]: That's how we got the ambitious Paris Accords through.

175
00:14:05,305 --> 00:14:10,551
[SPEAKER_03]: And turning our back on the European Union is turning our back on our best way of fighting the climate emergency.

176
00:14:10,953 --> 00:14:18,815
[SPEAKER_07]: It was Labour who put the climate emergency motion to Parliament on May 1st and led the way in the UK.

177
00:14:18,895 --> 00:14:25,975
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't think it is helping the planet

178
00:14:25,955 --> 00:14:28,238
[SPEAKER_04]: that much for us all to be squabbling with each other here.

179
00:14:28,258 --> 00:14:31,782
[SPEAKER_04]: This is something we should actually be trying to find unity and common purpose on.

180
00:14:31,822 --> 00:14:34,165
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, I'm proud of the fact that Scotland is leading the way.

181
00:14:34,185 --> 00:14:36,147
[SPEAKER_04]: The UN recognises us as a world leader.

182
00:14:36,447 --> 00:14:38,089
[SPEAKER_04]: COP will be in Glasgow next year.

183
00:14:38,149 --> 00:14:42,234
[SPEAKER_04]: And we should be agreeing that Scotland, the UK, should be leading the world.

184
00:14:42,254 --> 00:14:44,236
[SPEAKER_04]: And then we should be putting pressure on other countries.

185
00:14:44,277 --> 00:14:49,362
[SPEAKER_04]: Because right now, the world is not on track to limit temperature rises to 1.5 degrees.

186
00:14:49,382 --> 00:14:50,604
[SPEAKER_04]: We've heard your ambitions.

187
00:14:50,624 --> 00:14:54,088
[SPEAKER_04]: And let's make sure that we focus on the ambitions that we need to

188
00:14:54,068 --> 00:14:55,050
[SPEAKER_09]: We have heard your ambitions.

189
00:14:55,090 --> 00:15:00,662
[SPEAKER_09]: They range from 2030 to 2045 and 2050 in the case of the Conservatives.

190
00:15:00,682 --> 00:15:02,306
[SPEAKER_09]: But how are you all going to get there?

191
00:15:02,326 --> 00:15:04,090
[SPEAKER_09]: What will it mean for how we live our lives?

192
00:15:04,130 --> 00:15:05,513
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's start with food.

193
00:15:05,934 --> 00:15:09,982
[SPEAKER_09]: It makes up about a fifth of the UK's greenhouse gas emissions.

194
00:15:10,323 --> 00:15:12,668
[SPEAKER_09]: Sean Berry, how do we need to change that?

195
00:15:12,648 --> 00:15:17,573
[SPEAKER_00]: We absolutely need to look at every single layer of our society to do this.

196
00:15:17,673 --> 00:15:25,922
[SPEAKER_00]: Our Green New Deal looks at our homes, our industry, our energy, and very importantly, our agriculture, our food, and how we deal with our land.

197
00:15:26,303 --> 00:15:30,487
[SPEAKER_00]: At the moment, we focus far too much of our land on pasture.

198
00:15:30,847 --> 00:15:31,969
[SPEAKER_00]: We don't have enough woods.

199
00:15:32,269 --> 00:15:34,011
[SPEAKER_00]: We need to plant an awful lot more trees.

200
00:15:34,071 --> 00:15:36,674
[SPEAKER_00]: We need to rewild our landscape.

201
00:15:36,694 --> 00:15:37,855
[SPEAKER_00]: What about red leech?

202
00:15:37,895 --> 00:15:41,659
[SPEAKER_00]: And it means some of the landscapes that are currently being used for pasture land

203
00:15:41,639 --> 00:15:47,708
[SPEAKER_00]: for meat need to be changed to being forestry, need to be changed to being absorbing carbon as well.

204
00:15:47,768 --> 00:15:48,709
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's really important.

205
00:15:48,729 --> 00:15:51,573
[SPEAKER_09]: And you want to tax dairy and meat, don't you?

206
00:15:51,593 --> 00:15:52,535
[SPEAKER_00]: Just explain how that would work.

207
00:15:52,835 --> 00:15:56,901
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, our taxes are all absolutely revenue neutral.

208
00:15:57,101 --> 00:16:06,314
[SPEAKER_00]: Every single penny from the tax that we put on carbon and the tax we put on methane at the level of meat and dairy would go straight back into changing what's going on.

209
00:16:06,334 --> 00:16:07,596
[SPEAKER_00]: We're not about making money.

210
00:16:07,795 --> 00:16:10,260
[SPEAKER_00]: We're about changing how things happen.

211
00:16:10,340 --> 00:16:12,784
[SPEAKER_00]: And so, yeah, we want the industry to change.

212
00:16:12,804 --> 00:16:15,690
[SPEAKER_00]: We don't want any of those taxes to reach people's plates.

213
00:16:15,990 --> 00:16:24,786
[SPEAKER_00]: We want the industry to reduce the amount of meat that they're producing, to produce the greener, healthier choices, and make those the cheapest choices for everybody.

214
00:16:24,806 --> 00:16:27,331
[SPEAKER_00]: That's how the green values always work on these things.

215
00:16:27,351 --> 00:16:28,453
[SPEAKER_00]: We're about changing things.

216
00:16:28,433 --> 00:16:31,558
[SPEAKER_09]: Nicola Sturgeon, do we need to go plant-based?

217
00:16:31,578 --> 00:16:36,826
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we all have to think about the balanced, healthy diets that we eat.

218
00:16:36,846 --> 00:16:40,731
[SPEAKER_04]: We also have to think much more carefully about where our food is sourced from.

219
00:16:41,092 --> 00:16:46,560
[SPEAKER_04]: Absolutely, the practices that are used in agriculture and farming have to change, have to become

220
00:16:46,540 --> 00:16:49,624
[SPEAKER_04]: much more energy efficient and environmentally friendly.

221
00:16:49,844 --> 00:17:00,356
[SPEAKER_04]: But of course, again, talking about Scotland, we have the climate and the environment to actually support sustainable, high-quality produce, and we should be supporting our farmers to do that.

222
00:17:00,396 --> 00:17:04,380
[SPEAKER_04]: A lot has already been done just now, but we need to do more of that.

223
00:17:04,541 --> 00:17:06,183
[SPEAKER_04]: Land use, I absolutely agree about land use.

224
00:17:06,203 --> 00:17:10,067
[SPEAKER_04]: I've been listening to all of the parties here today talk about the number of trees

225
00:17:10,047 --> 00:17:11,049
[SPEAKER_04]: they want to plant.

226
00:17:11,190 --> 00:17:17,204
[SPEAKER_04]: Last year in Scotland, 22 million trees were planted, 84% of the UK total.

227
00:17:17,344 --> 00:17:21,113
[SPEAKER_09]: I want to talk about the food on people's plates.

228
00:17:21,134 --> 00:17:25,103
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you need to show leadership and say to people, you have got to eat less Aberdeen Angus?

229
00:17:25,083 --> 00:17:27,245
[SPEAKER_09]: And say to your farmers, you're going to have to sell this.

230
00:17:27,265 --> 00:17:32,111
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got to make sure that the food that we are producing is produced in a way that is more environmentally friendly.

231
00:17:32,131 --> 00:17:34,153
[SPEAKER_04]: There's a lot of work ongoing to do that right now.

232
00:17:34,453 --> 00:17:43,483
[SPEAKER_04]: But for environmental reasons and for health reasons, yes, of course, we've got to be encouraging people to eat balanced diets and to think about getting their food much more locally sourced.

233
00:17:43,503 --> 00:17:47,507
[SPEAKER_04]: That's good for the economy as well as being good for people's health and good for the environment.

234
00:17:47,587 --> 00:17:52,353
[SPEAKER_09]: Adam Price, are you prepared to tell your sheep and cattle farmers that people are going to have to eat less meat?

235
00:17:52,373 --> 00:17:52,693
[SPEAKER_09]: No.

236
00:17:52,673 --> 00:18:07,695
[SPEAKER_08]: No, it's an absolute myth actually that the IPCC report was somehow advocating moving away from meat and milk, the kind of produce that we produce in a temperate, wet, largely

237
00:18:07,675 --> 00:18:20,534
[SPEAKER_08]: wet climate like in Wales, actually animals fed on grassland make a positive contribution because grass is one of the most important stores of carbon that we have.

238
00:18:20,854 --> 00:18:26,983
[SPEAKER_08]: If you lose that, if you move away from that, actually you move to scrub etc, then you actually

239
00:18:26,963 --> 00:18:30,429
[SPEAKER_08]: actually lead to higher emissions as a result of that.

240
00:18:30,830 --> 00:18:39,865
[SPEAKER_08]: The real message on food, right, is that we, all of us, as individuals, public authorities, schools, NHS, etc., we need to be buying more locally.

241
00:18:39,885 --> 00:18:48,379
[SPEAKER_08]: We need to create local food systems producing the whole range, both of plant protein and animal protein, and stop importing it to the level we do.

242
00:18:48,439 --> 00:18:50,102
[SPEAKER_08]: And farmers are an important part

243
00:18:50,082 --> 00:18:58,856
[SPEAKER_08]: of the climate change that we want to create because they are custodians of the environment and we should be involving them as allies rather than decrying them as the enemies of...

244
00:18:58,876 --> 00:19:00,919
[SPEAKER_09]: I think you're the only one who's gone plant-based, aren't you?

245
00:19:00,939 --> 00:19:02,621
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, do the rest of us as well?

246
00:19:03,002 --> 00:19:03,503
[SPEAKER_09]: What's that, sir?

247
00:19:04,024 --> 00:19:06,087
[SPEAKER_09]: Going plant-based in terms of our diet.

248
00:19:06,307 --> 00:19:08,130
[SPEAKER_09]: You've gone there already, basically, haven't you?

249
00:19:08,150 --> 00:19:09,492
[SPEAKER_09]: Do the rest of us have to follow you?

250
00:19:09,472 --> 00:19:15,720
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I think meat consumption is falling anyway and more and more people are recognising that you need a balanced diet.

251
00:19:15,740 --> 00:19:23,589
[SPEAKER_07]: It doesn't mean everybody's got to become a vegetarian tomorrow and neither will they, but it does mean we have to look at the balance of our food sources as well.

252
00:19:23,930 --> 00:19:28,696
[SPEAKER_07]: Therefore, more UK production of fruit and vegetables is perfectly possible.

253
00:19:29,036 --> 00:19:32,340
[SPEAKER_07]: Looking at the issues of the damage we do to our environment by

254
00:19:32,320 --> 00:19:36,187
[SPEAKER_07]: but flying vegetables in from all over the world when they could be produced here.

255
00:19:36,468 --> 00:19:38,511
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a whole lot of issues surrounding that.

256
00:19:38,551 --> 00:19:48,229
[SPEAKER_07]: But we also have to recognize that many people in this country are actually obese because of the poor quality food that they eat, or hungry because they can't afford to eat properly.

257
00:19:48,249 --> 00:19:50,573
[SPEAKER_07]: So it is also about food pricing.

258
00:19:50,994 --> 00:19:53,198
[SPEAKER_07]: And with our farms, yes,

259
00:19:53,178 --> 00:19:55,141
[SPEAKER_07]: The farms are absolutely crucial to this.

260
00:19:55,241 --> 00:19:58,066
[SPEAKER_07]: It is about extending biodiversity on our farms.

261
00:19:58,126 --> 00:20:01,271
[SPEAKER_07]: It is about expanding headlands around fields.

262
00:20:01,431 --> 00:20:06,259
[SPEAKER_07]: It is about rewilding part of it in order to strengthen our levels of biodiversity.

263
00:20:06,279 --> 00:20:15,895
[SPEAKER_07]: If we go on damaging our soil at the rate we are, destroying the insect population at the rate we are, the levels of agricultural production will actually start to go down, not up.

264
00:20:15,875 --> 00:20:19,323
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's talk about another aspect of our lives and how it might have to change.

265
00:20:19,363 --> 00:20:22,551
[SPEAKER_09]: If that one doesn't have to change that radically, it sounds like it.

266
00:20:22,571 --> 00:20:27,522
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, Jo Swinson, how much do we have to change the amount we fly?

267
00:20:27,983 --> 00:20:30,248
[SPEAKER_09]: You want to tax us according to how we fly.

268
00:20:30,569 --> 00:20:30,930
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

269
00:20:30,910 --> 00:20:43,957
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, the international flights, obviously, the biggest amount of carbon released in terms of aviation, and we've said we would start with an international frequent flyer tax for those taking more than three return long-haul flights a year.

270
00:20:44,137 --> 00:20:44,578
[SPEAKER_03]: How much?

271
00:20:45,360 --> 00:20:50,530
[SPEAKER_03]: What it would mean is it would be more expensive for those taking more than three return flights a year.

272
00:20:50,550 --> 00:20:51,332
[SPEAKER_03]: What would you pay?

273
00:20:51,312 --> 00:20:54,878
[SPEAKER_03]: We've got the whole costing set, obviously it's on a scale.

274
00:20:54,898 --> 00:21:04,152
[SPEAKER_03]: So people who are flying very, very frequently, the people that are racking up those long haul flights will pay a lot more.

275
00:21:04,172 --> 00:21:12,966
[SPEAKER_03]: I haven't flown internationally on holiday for a very long time, but I do fly domestically and that is because I represent

276
00:21:12,946 --> 00:21:15,369
[SPEAKER_03]: a constituency of 400 miles from London.

277
00:21:15,489 --> 00:21:19,214
[SPEAKER_03]: And at the moment, we do not have good enough transport infrastructure.

278
00:21:19,234 --> 00:21:22,518
[SPEAKER_03]: We've got Victorian railway infrastructure, and we're in the 21st century.

279
00:21:22,599 --> 00:21:31,650
[SPEAKER_03]: That's why we need the investment in things like High Speed 2 to bring our domestic travel in the UK up to the standards it needs.

280
00:21:31,670 --> 00:21:32,912
[SPEAKER_03]: Hardly anyone

281
00:21:32,892 --> 00:21:38,477
[SPEAKER_03]: would think of flying between London and Paris or London and Brussels these days since the Eurostar came in.

282
00:21:38,838 --> 00:21:41,280
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the kind of 21st century infrastructure that we need.

283
00:21:41,460 --> 00:21:46,124
[SPEAKER_09]: Sian Berry, what would the impact of HS2 be on wildlife?

284
00:21:46,245 --> 00:21:50,669
[SPEAKER_00]: We are one of the only parties here, I think, who want to cancel HS2.

285
00:21:51,129 --> 00:21:59,457
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's the opportunity cost of investing in such a big project when we could be investing in the local sustainable transport

286
00:21:59,437 --> 00:22:00,740
[SPEAKER_00]: that people are crying out for.

287
00:22:00,780 --> 00:22:02,162
[SPEAKER_00]: People are trapped in their cars.

288
00:22:02,182 --> 00:22:03,385
[SPEAKER_00]: They want better buses.

289
00:22:03,645 --> 00:22:04,968
[SPEAKER_00]: They want better local transport.

290
00:22:04,988 --> 00:22:06,290
[SPEAKER_00]: They want to be able to walk and cycle.

291
00:22:06,551 --> 00:22:08,114
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's where we differ on HS2.

292
00:22:08,855 --> 00:22:10,498
[SPEAKER_00]: We like Eurostar.

293
00:22:10,518 --> 00:22:11,460
[SPEAKER_00]: We like high speed rail.

294
00:22:11,701 --> 00:22:16,089
[SPEAKER_00]: But that project at this moment, we could spend that money so much better in other places.

295
00:22:16,129 --> 00:22:18,694
[SPEAKER_09]: You want to extend HS2 right up

296
00:22:18,674 --> 00:22:19,896
[SPEAKER_09]: to Scotland, don't you?

297
00:22:19,916 --> 00:22:23,802
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't want Scotland to be left behind in these things, but we want to invest more in public transport.

298
00:22:23,862 --> 00:22:26,726
[SPEAKER_04]: In answer to your question earlier on, do people have to fly less?

299
00:22:26,746 --> 00:22:28,669
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, I think we do, where we can.

300
00:22:29,149 --> 00:22:33,696
[SPEAKER_04]: Something like half of all international flights are taken by 10% of the population.

301
00:22:34,197 --> 00:22:35,459
[SPEAKER_04]: So we have to invest more.

302
00:22:35,479 --> 00:22:39,224
[SPEAKER_04]: We are investing half a billion pounds to improve bus infrastructure.

303
00:22:39,244 --> 00:22:41,087
[SPEAKER_04]: We need to get the rail services.

304
00:22:41,067 --> 00:22:41,608
[SPEAKER_04]: better.

305
00:22:41,848 --> 00:22:50,182
[SPEAKER_04]: Where flights are necessary, in a country like Scotland, sometimes they are, we have set a target to decarbonise all flights within Scotland by 2040.

306
00:22:51,324 --> 00:23:03,784
[SPEAKER_04]: We have already one of the most comprehensive electric vehicle charging networks anywhere in Europe with a target of phasing out... Are you beseeching people to fly less or are you going to tax them to make sure they fly less?

307
00:23:03,764 --> 00:23:07,129
[SPEAKER_04]: The UK already has one of the highest levels of air passenger duty.

308
00:23:07,149 --> 00:23:13,918
[SPEAKER_04]: My party had a long-standing commitment to cut that, and we decided we couldn't do that, in all conscience, because of the climate emergency.

309
00:23:13,958 --> 00:23:18,525
[SPEAKER_04]: So, you know, I think we need to make sure the alternatives are there and encourage people.

310
00:23:18,545 --> 00:23:27,477
[SPEAKER_04]: But on all of this discussion about individual behaviour, important though it is, somebody made a point about the small number of companies responsible for the majority of emissions.

311
00:23:27,737 --> 00:23:31,763
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got to make sure that industry and government are leading by example.

312
00:23:31,743 --> 00:23:37,249
[SPEAKER_09]: Indeed, Jeremy Corbyn, Heathrow Airport is the single biggest emitter of greenhouse gases.

313
00:23:38,193 --> 00:23:40,504
[SPEAKER_09]: Are you in favour of giving it that third runway?

314
00:23:40,872 --> 00:23:52,867
[SPEAKER_07]: I voted against it at the time it came up, and we would set any expansion of any airport against tests on noise, on pollution, on sustainability, and on climate change targets.

315
00:23:52,887 --> 00:24:01,718
[SPEAKER_07]: And if we are to reduce the amount of flying going on, then we do have to invest in extending and expanding our rail network, and particularly the rail network into Europe.

316
00:24:02,018 --> 00:24:05,783
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, I looked at the price of going to Berlin the other week.

317
00:24:05,965 --> 00:24:09,873
[SPEAKER_07]: One airline was offering a £19 single ticket to go to Berlin.

318
00:24:10,455 --> 00:24:18,010
[SPEAKER_07]: To go by train would have cost £240 and the rail infrastructure was totally invested in by the public.

319
00:24:18,231 --> 00:24:21,578
[SPEAKER_07]: There has to be a much more efficient link-up.

320
00:24:21,558 --> 00:24:44,032
[SPEAKER_07]: of the Eurostar rail service with the whole of the rest of Europe in order to reduce the number of short-haul flights that go to Europe and there has to be an expansion of our rail network all across the country if we are to get people to use trains rather than flights and also make the train fares cheaper so that it is actually a real offer, an option for everybody in this country.

321
00:24:44,052 --> 00:24:47,717
[SPEAKER_09]: So cheap flights for the mayor have got to end, haven't they?

322
00:24:47,950 --> 00:24:57,804
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we do it better by offering a sensible alternative which is also, and I'll finish on this point, also about improving bus services all across the country.

323
00:24:57,844 --> 00:25:01,769
[SPEAKER_07]: They're pretty good in London, they're pretty poor in most other parts of the country.

324
00:25:01,809 --> 00:25:09,840
[SPEAKER_07]: There has to be full regulation and demand for provision of adequate bus services all over the country to cut down on air pollution from cars.

325
00:25:09,820 --> 00:25:17,649
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, just on the aviation point, I mean, we are very late, the rest of the parties here, to being against aviation expansion.

326
00:25:18,430 --> 00:25:23,937
[SPEAKER_00]: Just over a year ago, more than half of Labour MPs voted for Heathrow expansion.

327
00:25:24,177 --> 00:25:29,644
[SPEAKER_00]: The Lib Dems voted against, Plaid Cymru voted against, the SNP abstained, and you cannot abstain on climate change.

328
00:25:29,964 --> 00:25:31,626
[SPEAKER_00]: It's good that we're there now saying

329
00:25:31,606 --> 00:25:33,809
[SPEAKER_00]: we need to limit the amount of aviation.

330
00:25:33,989 --> 00:25:38,815
[SPEAKER_00]: The question now is how we share out the flights that we can take more fairly.

331
00:25:38,835 --> 00:25:45,023
[SPEAKER_00]: And that does mean targeting those 15% of people who take 70% of all flights.

332
00:25:45,263 --> 00:25:47,566
[SPEAKER_00]: These are the frequent flyers who need...

333
00:25:47,586 --> 00:25:52,112
[SPEAKER_00]: I will let you answer in a moment.

334
00:25:52,092 --> 00:25:56,243
[SPEAKER_08]: As Sian rightly says, we would cancel the third runway at Heathrow.

335
00:25:56,263 --> 00:25:58,208
[SPEAKER_08]: We would also cancel HS2.

336
00:25:58,308 --> 00:26:00,454
[SPEAKER_08]: It is a vanity project.

337
00:26:00,494 --> 00:26:01,537
[SPEAKER_08]: It is kind of obscene.

338
00:26:01,898 --> 00:26:07,232
[SPEAKER_08]: The suggestion is that England is going to get a high-speed north-south railway

339
00:26:07,212 --> 00:26:12,298
[SPEAKER_08]: we in Wales haven't got any kind of railway link north to south within our country.

340
00:26:12,338 --> 00:26:23,270
[SPEAKER_08]: We want to rectify that, bring back the Aberystwyth to Carmarthen railway link, take it up all the way to Caernarfon and Ynys Môn and see the proper investment in our transport infrastructure within Wales.

341
00:26:23,290 --> 00:26:31,279
[SPEAKER_08]: We only get 1% of the transport infrastructure investment in the UK, we've got 5% of the population and it's been like that for decades.

342
00:26:31,299 --> 00:26:33,642
[SPEAKER_08]: I have to say, Jeremy, under Labour governments as well.

343
00:26:33,622 --> 00:26:44,057
[SPEAKER_04]: One of the points I wanted to make, going back to the discussion about targets, is the UK government's target right now, the 2050 target, actually excludes aviation emissions from it.

344
00:26:44,338 --> 00:26:46,821
[SPEAKER_04]: Scotland's target includes aviation emissions.

345
00:26:47,182 --> 00:26:53,371
[SPEAKER_04]: And I suspect if the UK was to include emissions from aviation, Heathrow expansion would not align with that.

346
00:26:53,431 --> 00:27:01,463
[SPEAKER_04]: So we've got to make sure that these targets, if they are to be meaningful, are actually including all of the emissions and the biggest emitters along the way.

347
00:27:01,663 --> 00:27:02,785
[SPEAKER_04]: You have to include aviation.

348
00:27:02,765 --> 00:27:09,475
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's move on from transport.

349
00:27:09,756 --> 00:27:11,899
[SPEAKER_09]: Time is short, we want to get through quite a lot on this.

350
00:27:12,300 --> 00:27:14,984
[SPEAKER_09]: A third of our emissions come from our homes.

351
00:27:15,004 --> 00:27:19,230
[SPEAKER_09]: The Conservatives say they will invest over £9 billion on energy efficiency.

352
00:27:19,431 --> 00:27:28,705
[SPEAKER_09]: You all talk big on cutting that with insulation and zero carbon homes, but how are you actually going to make people change their heating systems?

353
00:27:28,938 --> 00:27:35,624
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I think the first thing that we can do, which is so important, is actually about retrofitting homes to insulate them properly.

354
00:27:36,145 --> 00:27:44,473
[SPEAKER_03]: And in terms of how we can encourage people to do that, well, that's actually going to be something which is good for people because it cuts energy bills, it helps people save money.

355
00:27:44,933 --> 00:27:57,865
[SPEAKER_03]: And for low-income households, that should be something which we do, that we make sure that that is done by the government so that those homes, within the next five years, are insulated to help cut fuel poverty, cut energy bills.

356
00:27:57,845 --> 00:28:04,295
[SPEAKER_03]: But the other thing we absolutely need to be doing and it's I mean it's madness and it's you know the Conservatives that have dropped this.

357
00:28:04,876 --> 00:28:09,263
[SPEAKER_03]: We know how to build homes that are zero carbon homes.

358
00:28:10,065 --> 00:28:16,615
